'''Erminio Spalla''' (7 July 1897 – 14 August 1971) was an Italian professional heavyweight [[boxer]], [[film actor]] and singer.

Spalla studied fine arts in [[Brera (district of Milan)|Brera]], when in 1910 he saw film footage of the world boxing championships and decided to become a professional boxer.
He was the first Italian to win a European boxing title, which he did in 1923. He lost it in 1926 to [[Paulino Uzcudun]] and retired from boxing the next year, though he briefly returned to the ring in 1934 and won all three of his final bouts.<ref name=page/>  He returned to art after retiring from the ring.

In October 1937 he debuted as an opera singer in ''Nel Trovatore'' in [[Turin]].<ref name=br/> In the same year he also worked in sculpture and painting.

In 1939 he acted in his first film, ''Io, suo padre'' by [[Mario Bonnard]]. This was followed by over fifty films and television series, including the war film ''[[Giarabub (film)|Giarabub]]'' (1942).<ref name=bio/> His last film was ''I fratelli Karamazov'' by [[Sandro Bolchi]] (1969).<ref name=bio/>

His elder brother Giuseppe was also a boxer.<ref name=br/>

